atoi(3)                                                                               Library Functions Manual                                                                               atoi(3)

NNAAMMEE
       atoi, atol, atoll - convert a string to an integer

LLIIBBRRAARRYY
       Standard C library (_l_i_b_c, _-_l_c)

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ##iinncclluuddee <<ssttddlliibb..hh>>

       iinntt aattooii((ccoonnsstt cchhaarr **_n_p_t_r));;
       lloonngg aattooll((ccoonnsstt cchhaarr **_n_p_t_r));;
       lloonngg lloonngg aattoollll((ccoonnsstt cchhaarr **_n_p_t_r));;

   Feature Test Macro Requirements for glibc (see ffeeaattuurree__tteesstt__mmaaccrrooss(7)):

       aattoollll():
           _ISOC99_SOURCE
               || /* glibc <= 2.19: */ _BSD_SOURCE || _SVID_SOURCE

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       The aattooii() function converts the initial portion of the string pointed to by _n_p_t_r to _i_n_t.  The behavior is the same as

           strtol(nptr, NULL, 10);

       except that aattooii() does not detect errors.

       The aattooll() and aattoollll() functions behave the same as aattooii(), except that they convert the initial portion of the string to their return type of _l_o_n_g or _l_o_n_g _l_o_n_g.

RREETTUURRNN VVAALLUUEE
       The converted value or 0 on error.

AATTTTRRIIBBUUTTEESS
       For an explanation of the terms used in this section, see aattttrriibbuutteess(7).

       ┌───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────┬────────────────┐
       │IInntteerrffaaccee                                                                                                                                                  │ AAttttrriibbuuttee     │ VVaalluuee          │
       ├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────┼────────────────┤
       │aattooii(), aattooll(), aattoollll()                                                                                                                                    │ Thread safety │ MT-Safe locale │
       └───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────┴────────────────┘

SSTTAANNDDAARRDDSS
       POSIX.1-2001, POSIX.1-2008, C99, SVr4, 4.3BSD.

NNOOTTEESS
       POSIX.1 leaves the return value of aattooii() on error unspecified.  On glibc, musl libc, and uClibc, 0 is returned on error.

BBUUGGSS
       _e_r_r_n_o  is not set on error so there is no way to distinguish between 0 as an error and as the converted value.  No checks for overflow or underflow are done.  Only base-10 input can be con‐
       verted.  It is recommended to instead use the ssttrrttooll() and ssttrrttoouull() family of functions in new programs.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       aattooff(3), ssttrrttoodd(3), ssttrrttooll(3), ssttrrttoouull(3)

